Author-Name:  Nicholas Bloom 
Author-Name:  Raffaella Sadun 
Title: The Organization of Firms Across Countries 
Abstract:
 We argue that social capital as proxied by trust increases aggregate
 productivity by affecting the organization of firms. To do this we collect
 new data on the decentralization of investment, hiring, production, and
 sales decisions from corporate headquarters to local plant managers in
 almost 4,000 firms in the United States, Europe, and Asia. We find that
 firms headquartered in high-trust regions are significantly more likely to
 decentralize. To help identify causal effects, we look within
 multinational firms and show that higher levels of bilateral trust between
 the multinational's country of origin and subsidiary's country of location
 increases decentralization, even after instrumenting trust using religious
 similarities between the countries. Finally, we show evidence suggesting
 that trust raises aggregate productivity by facilitating reallocation
 between firms and allowing more efficient firms to grow, as CEOs can
 decentralize more decisions.  Copyright 2012, Oxford University Press.
